Life-cycle and Phases

This lesson explains the lifecycle in the context of Maven. We also discuss phases that make up a lifecycle.

We'll cover the following
  • Build lifecycle

Build lifecycle#

Maven supports the concept of a build lifecycle which can be loosely defined as an ordered set of actions Maven takes for building and distributing a particular artifact or project.

A build life cycle consists of build phases where each phase has plugin goals attached to it. The plugin goals are executed when the phase executes as part of the life cycle.

Let’s look at an example; one of the lifecycles is the clean lifecycle which consists of the following phases:

  1. pre-clean,
  2. clean, (don’t confuse the phase with the lifecycle, which is also named clean)
  3. post-clean.

Note that the phases of a lifecycle always execute in order, i.e., pre-clean will execute first, clean next, and finally post-clean. Within each phase, plugin goals that are bound to the phase are executed. A build phase without any goals bound to it isn’t executed.

As an exercise, let’s run the clean phase of the clean lifecycle in the EmptyProject using mvn clean. Note that we specify the phase alongside the mvn command. When we execute the clean phase, the phase previous to it, i.e., pre-clean, will also execute if it has any plugin goals bound to it.

# Change directory to Empty Project
cd /EmptyProject
# Run mvn clean
mvn clean

W

When we run mvn clean in the project directory EmptyProject, we see the following result:

The output shows the clean goal of maven-clean-plugin being executed in the clean build phase of the clean lifecycle.

[INFO] --- maven-clean-plugin:2.5:clean (default-clean) @ empty-project ---

You can observe that even though we invoked the build phase clean, the build phase before it, i.e., pre-clean, doesn’t execute. A build phase without any plugin goals bound to it does not execute. One way we can change that is by adding the following snippet to the POM file.

<build>
<plugins>
<plugin>
   <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
   <artifactId>maven-clean-plugin</artifactId>
   <version>2.5</version>
   <executions>
     <execution>
       <phase>pre-clean</phase>
       <goals>
         <goal>clean</goal>
       </goals>
     </execution>
   </executions>
 </plugin>
</plugins>
</build>

With the above changes, we bind the goal clean of the maven-clean-plugin with the build phase pre-clean. Now if we execute mvn clean we’ll see the same clean goal is executed twice as shown below:

We’ll learn in detail how to bind plugin goals to phases, but for now it is enough to know that plugin goals can be attached to build phases. Another important point is that a plugin goal can be attached to more than one build phases as we just saw in the exercise above.

So, at this point you may ask, what exactly does the clean goal do? The clean plugin details can be found here. In fact, anyone can write a plugin that can be used by others. The clean plugin has a single goal, clean, that deletes the artifacts produced during a build in the project’s working directory.

We can do something more interesting in the pre-clean phase. We can tie the goal, run, of the maven-antrun-plugin to the pre-clean phase and print a message. This plugin is used to execute ant tasks in a maven build. Ant is a build tool that pre-dated Maven and has the concept of tasks. One of the tasks is echo which prints a message on the console, which we’ll be using. More information about the plugin can be found here. The required plugin snippet in the POM file is presented below:

            <plugin>
                <groupId>
                    org.apache.maven.plugins
                </groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-antrun-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.0.0</version>
                <executions>
                    <execution>
                        <id>1</id>
                        <phase>pre-clean</phase>
                        <goals>
                            <goal>run</goal>
                        </goals>
                        <configuration>
                            <target>
                                <echo level="info">Learning Maven: pre-clean</echo>
                            </target>
                        </configuration>
                    </execution>

                    <execution>
                        <id>2</id>
                        <phase>post-clean</phase>
                        <goals>
                            <goal>run</goal>
                        </goals>
                        <configuration>
                            <target>
                                <echo level="info">Learning Maven: post-clean</echo>
                            </target>
                        </configuration>
                    </execution>

                </executions>
            </plugin>

The above snippet says that when the clean lifecycle’s pre-clean or post-clean build phase executes, it then runs the goal run, of the plugin maven-antrun-plugin with the provided configuration. In the exercise below, we build a project that has the run goal tied to both pre-clean and post-clean build phases of the clean lifecycle. We run mvn clean first and then mvn post-clean and observe the results.

The output of mvn post-clean is shown below:

We can see that the string “Learning Maven: pre-clean” and the string “Learning Maven: post-clean” are printed in the output indicating the phases pre-clean, clean, and post-clean all executed. When we run the command mvn clean, the second message will not be printed on the console as the phase post-clean will not run.
